    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1879-10-09T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1879-10-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="343" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d343">
                <head>No. 314.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bingham</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Evarts</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">United
                                        States Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Tokei,
                                        Japan</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1879-10-09">
                            <hi rend="italic">October</hi> 9, 1879</date>.
                                (Received November 4.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 987.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to my No. 961, wherein I
                            reported the order of this government making the silver yen a legal
                            tender, I now have the honor <pb facs="0792" n="696" xml:id="pg_696"/>
                            to further acquaint you that the same is being produced at the imperial
                            mint of Japan at the rate of 30,000 per day, and that it is rapidly
                            expelling from trade the Mexican dollar, so long the currency of this
                            empire.</p>
                <p>As the gold yen is also legal tender, this government has established the
                            bimetallic standard in Japan.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>JNO. A. BINGHAM.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
